                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d508">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.51/6240a: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1936-10-14T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >October 14, 1936—6 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>375. Today’s press under London date line October 13 states “The British Treasury
                    has agreed in principle to grant Government credits to China” and that
                    “Premature disclosure that the British Government’s export credits guarantee
                    department was contemplating granting credits to facilitate British trade with
                    China has delayed official announcement of the scheme, which may not now be
                    revealed in detail before next week”.</p>
                <p>Report by telegraph such information as may be available in regard to foregoing
                    and keep Department currently informed.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
